\parindent 0pt \parskip 6pt
\vspace{-20pt}

Using vector notation, a plane can be expressed as a point
$\mathbf{p}$ and an unit normal vector $\mathbf{N}$ at $\mathbf{p}$.

Given a vector $\mathbf{L}$ that is incident onto the plane at
$\mathbf{p}$, the projection $\mathbf{z}$ of $\mathbf{L}$ onto
$\mathbf{N}$ is
%
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{z} = ( \mathbf{L} \cdot \mathbf{N} ) \, \mathbf{N}\,.
\end{equation}

The projection $\mathbf{x}$ of $\mathbf{L}$ onto the intersection of the
given plane and one orthogonal to $\mathbf{L} \times \mathbf{N}$ is
%
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{L} - \mathbf{z} \,.
\end{equation}

The projection $\mathbf{r}$ of the reflecting vector $\mathbf{R}$ onto the
same intersection is $\mathbf{r} = \mathbf{x}$.

We have, trivially,
%
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{L} = \mathbf{z} + ( \mathbf{L} - \mathbf{z} ) \,.
\end{equation}

The projection $\mathbf{r}$ of the reflecting vector $\mathbf{R}$ onto the
same intersection is $\mathbf{r} = \mathbf{x}$.  The reflection must
reverse the projection onto $\mathbf{N}$.  Therefore the projection of 
$\mathbf{R}$ onto $\mathbf{N}$ is $-\mathbf{z}$, and we have, trivially,
%
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{R} = \mathbf{x} - \mathbf{z}
           = ( \mathbf{L} - \mathbf{z} ) - \mathbf{z} \,. \\
\end{equation}

From this, we have
%
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{R} = \mathbf{L} - 2 \, \mathbf{z} =
 \mathbf{L} - 2 \, ( \mathbf{L} \cdot \mathbf{N} ) \, \mathbf{N}\,.
\end{equation}

Because $\mathbf{N}$ is normal, $|\mathbf{L}|^2 = |\mathbf{x}|^2 +
|\mathbf{z}|^2 = |\mathbf{R}|^2$.  If $|\mathbf{L}| = |\mathbf{N}|=1$,
then $|\mathbf{R}|=1$.

If $\mathbf{N}$ is a normal vector that is not necessarily an unit normal
vector, we have
%
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{R} = \mathbf{L} - 2 \, \frac{\mathbf{L} \cdot \mathbf{N}}
                                    { | \mathbf{N} |^2 } \mathbf{N}
\end{equation}

